Data transformation functions¶

In [2]:
def fix_dict(dict_,date):
    dict_['date'] = date
    
    if dict_['longitude']=='null':
        dict_['longitude'] = None
        
    if dict_['latitude']=='null':
        dict_['latitude'] = None
    
    if dict_['location']=='null':
        dict_['location'] = None

    dict_['timestamp'] = dict_['timestamp'][:-3]
    
    dict_.pop('unique_key', None)
    dict_ = {k.capitalize():v for k,v in dict_.items()}
    return dict_

def fix_address(address):
    if 'BLOCK' in address:
        char = address.index('BLOCK')
        new_address = address[char:]
    else:
        new_address = address
    return new_address

Creating the GBQ Table¶

In [6]:
from google.cloud import bigquery

PROJECT_ID = "bi-psel"
DATASET_ID = "samyr_neto"
TABLE_ID = "austin_data"

client = bigquery.Client()

# 1) create table
schema = [
            bigquery.SchemaField("Descript", "STRING", mode="REQUIRED"),
            bigquery.SchemaField("Date", "DATE", mode="REQUIRED"),
            bigquery.SchemaField("Time", "TIME", mode="REQUIRED"),
            bigquery.SchemaField("Address", "STRING", mode="REQUIRED"),
            bigquery.SchemaField("Longitude", "FLOAT", mode="NULLABLE"),
            bigquery.SchemaField("Latitude", "FLOAT", mode="NULLABLE"),
            bigquery.SchemaField("Location", "STRING", mode="NULLABLE"),
            bigquery.SchemaField("Timestamp", "TIMESTAMP", mode="REQUIRED")
         ]

table = bigquery.Table(f"{PROJECT_ID}.{DATASET_ID}.{TABLE_ID}", schema=schema)
table = client.create_table(table)

Function creation¶

Now we will define the function responsible for taking a date string as an input, retrieving the information related to that particular date, and uploading this information into our Google Big Query table.

In [7]:
def load_data(date_string):
    global schema,table,client,gcs_file_system
    rows_to_insert = []
    try:
        datetime.datetime.strptime(date_string, '%Y-%m-%d')
    except ValueError:
        raise ValueError("Incorrect date format,input should be YYYY-MM-DD")
        
    gcs_json_path = "gs://arquivei-austin-incidents/{}/incidents.ndjson".format(date_string)
    
    with gcs_file_system.open(gcs_json_path) as f:
        json_data = [json.loads(line) for line in f]
    
    for single_json in json_data:
        single_json = fix_dict(single_json,date_string)
        rows_to_insert.append(single_json)

    client.insert_rows(rows = rows_to_insert,table = table,selected_fields = schema)
    return

Demonstrational SQL Queries¶

All of the next filters could be easily done using the Pandas library. The following queries are for demonstrational purposes only, showing that you can apply SQL queries to retrieve information from GBQ and saving them in a dataframe. We will only use the second query.

In [13]:
# counting descripts 
descript_value_counts_query = """SELECT Descript,COUNT(Descript) AS value_counts 
                                 FROM `bi-psel.samyr_neto.austin_data`
                                 GROUP BY (Descript) 
                                 ORDER BY  value_counts DESC"""

# returning data containing geographical information
geo_data_query = """SELECT *
                    FROM `bi-psel.samyr_neto.austin_data`
                    WHERE Longitude is not null"""

# counting crimes per month. (With BigQuery, you cannot use the derived column within the same select,
# hence the subquery)
crimes_per_month_query ="""SELECT year_month,COUNT(year_month) AS value_counts
                            FROM (
                                SELECT LEFT(CAST(Timestamp as string),7) AS year_month
                                FROM `bi-psel.samyr_neto.austin_data`
                                )
                            GROUP BY year_month
                            ORDER BY value_counts DESC"""

It looks like crime rate skyrockets towards the end of the 2015. There is a clear trend starting from month 8, reaching its peak at month 12. We have no data on the first month of 2015.

Analyzing the plot behavior of 2016, we can conclude that the trend continues up until month 3. For some reason, crime occurrences are plummeted at month 4. We can draw many hypothesis on why this happens, however, blindly guessing is out of the scope. Crime occurrences stay relatively low, tripling from month 7 to 8.

Most dangerous areas¶

When we first printed our dataframe at the beggining of the code, we could see at first glance that most of the showing addresses contained the word 'BLOCK' in it. Lets see if the addresses registered are indeed blocks:

In [35]:

print(f'{df_2016[df_2016["Address"].str.contains("BLOCK")].shape[0]/df_2016.shape[0]} of 2016 data has "BLOCK" in its address')

0.9764507989907485 of 2015 data has "BLOCK" in its address
0.9190767265760423 of 2016 data has "BLOCK" in its address

Yes. The vast majority of our data points occurred in some block. Now we need to remove the address number to group the same blocks.

In [38]:
for data,blocks,year,crimes in zip([df_2015,df_2016],[top_10_blocks_2015,top_10_blocks_2016],['2015','2016'],[crimes_2015,crimes_2016]):
    grouped_block_crimes = data[data['Block'].isin(blocks.index)] # selecting crimes that occured in blocks displayed above
    grouped_block_crimes = grouped_block_crimes[grouped_block_crimes['Descript'].isin(crimes.head(5).index)] # selecting only top 5 crimes in order to make the plot understandable
    tmp = grouped_block_crimes.groupby(['Descript','Block']).size().reset_index() # creating the desired groupby object
    tmp.reset_index(inplace=True) # converting it to a dataframe by reseting the index
    tmp.rename(columns={0:'counts'},inplace=True) # renaming the count columns
    tmp=tmp.pivot(index='Block',columns='Descript',values='counts') # pivoting the dataframe to achieve the desired structure to be plotted
    tmp.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True,figsize=(25,15))
    plt.title(f'Top 5 Incidents distribution for each of the most dangerous blocks - {year}',fontdict={'fontsize': 35})

Conclusion¶

From the available data, we can draw the following conclusions:

  1. Crimes tend to be concentrated at the center of the city.
  2. Crimes in 2015 have risen considerably after month 8, reaching its peak at month 12. In 2016, crimes were steadily rising until month 4, in which crime rate plummeted and stayed relatively low, but slowly rising again.
  3. The most common crimes in 2015 were:
    • Theft
    • Lost Property
    • Identity theft
    • Theft of service (using a service without paying for it)
    • Harassment
  4. The most common crimes in 2016 were:
    • Crash/leaving the scene
    • Theft
    • Family disturbance
    • Burglary of vehicle
    • Criminal Trespass Notice
  5. Only 14 of the top 30 most common crimes in 2015 and 2016 are mutually shared.
  6. The 5 most common crimes in 2015 followed the overall trend. It is safe to say that theft has a great influence over the large spike at month 12.
  7. The 5 most common crimes in 2016 followed exactly the overall trend.
  8. In 2015, crimes occurred mostly at 6 and 18.
  9. In 2016, we can see an inverted bell curve, with crime occurrences well distributed throught the day, with a notable decrease towards the middle of the day.
  10. The most dangerous blocks of 2015 were:
    • Block E 8th St.
    • Block N Lamar Blvd
    • Block N IH 35 SVRD NB
    • Block Burnet RD
    • Block S IH 35 SVRD SB
  11. The most dangerous blocks of 2016 were:
    • Block N Lamar Blvd
    • Block N IH 35 SVRD NB
    • BLock N IH 35 SVRD SB
    • Block E Riverside DR
    • Block E 6th St.
  12. In 2015, theft occurred frequently in the most dangerous blocks. Curiously, Block E 8th. St, the most dangerous block of 2015, had no theft.
  13. In 2016, criminal trespass and theft occurred frequently in the most dangerous blocks.

Notes¶

Our data sample of 2016 is much larger than 2015. This should be considered when taking any data driven decisions. Theoretically, using the data from 2016 will be safer due to its larger sample size. One possible (and very viable) approach is to mix them together, since the 2016 data will heavily weight the results. They have been treated separately out of curiosity to investigate their differences.
